              <div class="content__page-desc">

                <h3>Electric Coil Cooktops</h3>
                <p>
                  Electric coil cooktops are known for their durability and simplicity, but they are not without their maintenance needs. Common repair issues include malfunctioning burners, which may either fail to heat properly or not heat at all. This can often be attributed to a faulty burner element or a bad connection between the burner and the cooktop. Replacing a defective coil is generally straightforward and can cost between <b>$50 and $150</b>, including labor. Another common issue is a faulty infinite switch, which controls the heat level of the burners. Replacing this switch can range from <b>$100 to $200</b>. Regular cleaning and ensuring that the coils are properly seated can help prevent many of these issues, extending the lifespan of the cooktop.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Smooth-Top Electric Cooktops</h3>
                <p>
                  Smooth-top electric cooktops, featuring either radiant or induction heating elements, offer a sleek appearance and easy cleaning but come with their own set of repair challenges. Cracked glass tops are a frequent issue and can be quite costly to replace, often running between <b>$200 and $600</b> depending on the model and labor costs. Burners that fail to heat can be due to faulty heating elements or issues with the control board. Repairing or replacing these components can cost between <b>$150 and $400</b>. Induction cooktops, in particular, may require specialized service due to their advanced technology, which can increase repair costs. Regular care, such as avoiding heavy impacts on the glass surface and using appropriate cookware, can mitigate some of these issues.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Gas Cooktops</h3>
                <p>
                  Gas cooktops are favored for their precise temperature control and quick heating capabilities, but they require regular maintenance to function safely and efficiently. Common repair needs include fixing ignition problems, which can result from clogged burner ports or faulty igniters. Repairing or replacing an igniter typically costs between <b>$100 and $300</b>. Gas leaks are a more serious issue that requires immediate attention from a professional, and repairs can range from <b>$150 to $500</b> depending on the severity and location of the leak. Ensuring that gas lines, valves, and connections are secure and clean can help prevent many common issues. Regular cleaning of burner ports and grates can also enhance performance and longevity.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Modular Cooktops</h3>
                <p>
                  Modular cooktops offer the flexibility of combining different cooking elements, such as gas, electric, and induction modules, within the same unit. While this versatility is a significant advantage, it also means that repair needs can vary widely depending on the specific modules in use. Each type of module will have its own common issues, such as burner problems in gas modules or heating element failures in electric modules. Repair costs can range from <b>$100 to $500</b>, depending on the complexity of the issue and the module type. Because modular cooktops can involve multiple technologies, it is often advisable to consult specialized technicians who are familiar with the specific components involved. Regular maintenance, including cleaning and inspecting each module, can help prevent issues and extend the overall lifespan of the cooktop.
                </p>
