                <ul>
                  <li><b>Frequent Breakdowns: </b>If your range has needed multiple repairs in a short period, this is a sign that it might be time to replace it. Continuous issues can be both inconvenient and costly.</li>
                  <li><b>One-Time Repair: </b>For a range that has been reliable and only now needs a single, relatively minor repair, fixing it might be the better option.</li>
              </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Evaluate Performance and Efficiency</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><b>Energy Efficiency: </b>Older ranges tend to be less energy-efficient compared to newer models. Replacing an old range with an energy-efficient model can result in long-term savings on utility bills.</li>
                  <li><b>Performance Issues: </b>If your range struggles to maintain consistent temperatures, heats unevenly, or has other performance issues, a new model might provide better results and improve your cooking experience.</li>
              </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Safety Considerations</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><b>Gas Leaks and Electrical Issues: </b>Problems such as gas leaks or electrical malfunctions pose significant safety risks. If these issues are recurring, replacing the range is the safer option.</li>
                  <li><b>Outdated Features: </b>Modern ranges come with enhanced safety features such as automatic shut-off and advanced temperature controls. Upgrading to a newer model can provide added peace of mind.</li>
              </ul>
              </div>
              
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Environmental Impact</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><b> Eco-Friendly Models: </b>Newer ranges are often more environmentally friendly, with better energy efficiency and lower emissions. Replacing an old, inefficient range can reduce your carbon footprint.</li>
                  <li><b>Recycling Options: </b>When replacing your range, look into recycling programs that ensure your old appliance is disposed of in an environmentally responsible manner.</li>
              </ul>
              </div>
              
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Personal Preferences and Needs</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><b>Modern Features: </b>Consider whether you want the latest features such as smart technology, convection cooking, or self-cleaning options. If these features are important to you, upgrading might be worthwhile.</li>
                  <li><b> Aesthetic Appeal: </b>A new range can enhance the look of your kitchen and match other modern appliances, improving the overall aesthetic and value of your home.</li>
              </ul>
              </div>
              
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Consult a Professional</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><b>Expert Opinion: </b>Sometimes, the decision isn’t clear-cut. Consulting a professional technician can provide you with valuable insights into the condition of your range and help you make an informed decision.</li>
              </ul>
              </div>
              
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Summary</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><b>Repair: </b>Opt for repair if the range is relatively new, the repair cost is low, and the appliance has been reliable overall.</li>
                  <li><b>Replace: </b>Consider replacement if the range is old, repair costs are high, performance is poor, or if there are recurring safety issues.</li>
              </ul>

              <p>By weighing these factors carefully, you'll be better equipped to decide whether repairing or replacing your range is the best course of action.</p>
